{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4aea6f66-bb62-403f-a7eb-031b2ac93cd5","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, shared by all 3 projects)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n- **`EnableMSTestRunner`** — activates the MTP-based MSTest runner (bundled in MSTest 3.8.0).\n- **`OutputType Exe`** — required because each test project now runs as its own executable.\n- **`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** — lets `dotnet test` delegate to the MTP runner instead of VSTest.\n\n## 2. Each test `.csproj` — add the TRX extension\n\nMTP doesn't include TRX logging by default. Add this package to each test project (or in `Directory.Build.props` / `Directory.Packages.props`):\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.3\" />\n```\n\n## 3. CI command change\n\nReplace:\n```bash\ndotnet test --logger trx\n```\nwith:\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` arguments from MTP runner arguments. `--report-trx` is the MTP equivalent of `--logger trx`. Output goes to `TestResults/` by default; use `--report-trx-filename <name>.trx` to customize.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of per-project changes:** Only the new `PackageReference`. Everything else goes in `Directory.Build.props` so it's consistent across all three projects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73ea5021-d232-4d6d-a954-c53fd8d3ccdf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Enable MTP in each project** - Add `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` or use the newer property `<UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>`. For MSTest 3.8.0, the property is `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`.\n\n\n2. **Configure project settings** - Since MSTest 3.8.0 includes the built-in runner, I need to set `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` to activate it, change the output type to executable so tests run as standalone programs, and optionally enable `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` for additional platform integration.\n\n3. **Handle TRX logging** - The TRX report extension package needs to be added as a dependency, then configured through project properties or runsettings rather than using the older `--logger trx` syntax from VSTest.\n\n4. **For `dotnet test` compatibility** - When using the dotnet test bridge with MTP, the `--logger trx` flag won't translate directly. Instead, I'd need to pass `-- --report-trx` to forward the argument through to the MTP runner, or configure it in the project file itself.\n\nI'm thinking the cleanest approach here is to use a shared `Directory.Build.props` file to set these properties consistently across all projects. With the MTP bridge, `--logger trx` won't work since that's a VSTest argument. Instead, I need to use `--report-trx` passed directly to the test runner via `dotnet test -- --report-trx`. I'm not entirely certain if newer SDK versions handle the translation automatically, so I'll recommend the explicit MTP approach to be safe and give the user clear guidance.","outputTokens":1575,"requestId":"342E:362770:70C7677:7D1ED00:69F3FA70"},"id":"2534ba4d-a68e-46fc-8a04-8c51f9e526db","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:57:51.450Z","parentId":"8985ca97-2f46-4956-b5e3-dc4cebd13edc"}
